<p><img width="406" height="232" src="https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/bug-406x232.jpg" class="attachment-post-list size-post-list wp-post-image" alt="" decoding="async" loading="lazy" srcset="https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/bug-406x232.jpg 406w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/bug-300x171.jpg 300w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/bug-750x429.jpg 750w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/bug-350x200.jpg 350w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/bug-768x439.jpg 768w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/bug.jpg 840w " sizes="(max-width: 406px) 100vw, 406px" />The recent update to AppArmor to remedy issues with 3rd-party apps being unable to run on Ubuntu 24.04 LTS (due to its security hardening) inadvertently prevents a fleet of popular Flatpak apps from running either. The Telegram Desktop, KeePassXC, and Steam clients are among Flatpak apps users have reported issues with, seemingly due to the AppArmor profile tweaks for the Bubblewrap sandboxing tool the prior update introduced. To be clear: snap, DEB, and binary versions of the software above are not affected, only Flatpak packages installed from stores like Flathub. But good news: Ubuntu&#8217;s developers got to work to identify [&#8230;]</p>
